04712nam a22006855i 9781575064642DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a2016020811  a97815750646427 a10.1515/97815750646422doi  a(DE-B1597)606811  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA00aPJ3791b.B67 2016 4aPJ3791 7aREL0060002bisacsh04a809/.933542231 aBosworth, David A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInfant Weeping in Akkadian, Hebrew, and Greek Literature /cDavid A. Bosworth. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Studies in the Hebrew Bible ;v800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Infant Crying -- tChapter 2 Infant Crying in Mesopotamia -- tChapter 3 Weeping in Infant Abandonment Stories in the Old Testament -- tChapter 4 Weeping in Infant Abandonment Stories in Ancient Greek Literature -- tChapter 5 Comparative Perspectives -- tAppendix Concordance of Baby Incantations -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex of Ancient and Modern Authors -- tIndex of Scripture -- tIndex of Other Ancient Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThose who have spent time within earshot of a crying baby know the stress this sound can induce. Considerable scientific research has been devoted to the causes and consequences of infant crying because it is a public health concern implicated in parental frustration and infant abuse. Infant Weeping seeks to draw on the extensive research on infant crying in order to understand better the motif of infant weeping in ancient literature. The present book contributes to the growing interest in correlating scientific and humanities scholarship.Scientific research can help bridge the cultural distance that separates modern readers from ancient texts. For example, the Akkadian incantations for soothing infants may appear to be strange magical texts from a foreign world (which they are), but they also reflect common human realities that have been part of the parent-infant relationship in all times and cultures. The incantations reflect and evoke emotions and responses familiar to anyone who has cared for a baby. Fuller understanding of the dynamics of the parent-child relationship can help us see commonalities across differences and make foreign texts more interesting and relevant.David Bosworth draws on the natural sciences to develop a theory for analyzing infant weeping in literature. He then analyzes ancient Akkadian magical incantations for soothing crying babies as well as portions of the Babylonian Creation and Flood stories; in the Hebrew Bible, he explores two infant abandonment stories (Genesis 21 and Exodus 2) and the many parallels between them that have been overlooked; finally he examines a select corpus of Greek infant abandonment stories, including stories found in Herodotus, Sophocles, and Diodorus, among other authors. He ultimately places these textual corpuses in comparison with one another.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAbandoned childrenxBiblical teaching. 0aCrying in infants. 0aGreek literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aIncantations, Assyro-Babylonian. 7aRELIGION / Bible / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575064642zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575064642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781575064642/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA1